If you want to define **core expertise in C++**, 
think of it as the *non-negotiable foundation* every strong C++ developer must master—especially useful for system-level, high-performance, or library development (which fits your goals well).

Here’s a **clean, structured roadmap of core expertise topics in C++**:

---

# 1. Language Fundamentals (Must be rock solid)

* Value vs Reference semantics
* Lvalue / Rvalue / Move semantics
* Const correctness
* Type system (`auto`, `decltype`, type inference)
* Memory layout (stack vs heap)
* Undefined Behavior (very important)

---

# 2. Object-Oriented & Class Design

* Rule of 3 / 5 / 0
* Constructors / Destructors
* Copy vs Move
* Operator overloading
* Encapsulation & abstraction
* Polymorphism (runtime vs compile-time)

---

# 3. Templates & Generic Programming (Core strength)

* Function templates
* Class templates
* Variadic templates
* Template specialization
* SFINAE (Substitution Failure Is Not An Error)
* Concepts (C++20)

👉 This is what separates **average vs expert C++ dev**

---

# 4. STL (Standard Template Library)

* Containers:

  * `vector`, `list`, `deque`
  * `set`, `map`, `unordered_map`
* Iterators (very important concept)
* Algorithms:

  * `std::sort`, `std::transform`, `std::find`
* Functors & Lambdas

---

# 5. Memory Management (Critical for core C++)

* `new` / `delete`
* Smart pointers:

  * `unique_ptr`
  * `shared_ptr`
  * `weak_ptr`
* RAII (Resource Acquisition Is Initialization)
* Custom allocators (advanced)

---

# 6. Compile-Time vs Runtime Programming

* `constexpr`
* `consteval`
* Template metaprogramming
* CRTP (Curiously Recurring Template Pattern)

---

# 7. Low-Level & System Understanding

* Pointers & pointer arithmetic
* Bit manipulation
* Memory alignment
* Cache locality
* Endianness

---

# 8. Concurrency & Multithreading

* `std::thread`
* Mutex (`std::mutex`, `lock_guard`)
* Condition variables
* Atomic operations
* Thread safety patterns

---

# 9. Design Patterns in C++

(You already like this area 👍)

* Creational: Singleton, Factory
* Structural: Adapter, Decorator
* Behavioral: Observer, Strategy, Command
* Modern C++ patterns (RAII-based designs)

---

# 10. File I/O & System Interaction

* File streams (`fstream`)
* Binary vs text handling
* Serialization basics
* OS interaction basics

---

# 11. Debugging & Performance

* Valgrind / sanitizers
* Profiling
* Memory leaks detection
* Optimization techniques

---

# 12. Build System & Project Structure

* CMake (very important in real world)
* Static vs shared libraries
* Modular project design

---

# If You Want “Core C++ Expert Level”

Focus deeply on:

* Templates + STL internals
* Memory management
* Concurrency
* Low-level behavior

---

# Reality Insight

A **true core C++ expert** can:

* Write code without relying heavily on external libraries
* Understand performance at CPU/memory level
* Build systems like:

  * Game engines (console-based like you’re doing)
  * Database engines
  * Networking tools
  * Embedded simulations

